<TEXT>
new government figures show that farmers last 
year got the smallest portion of the food shoppers dollar since 
the agriculture department began compiling such figures 75 years 
ago 
according to revised figures by the departments economic 
research service the farm value of the retail cost of a market 
basket of food sold in grocery stores in 1987 was 30 percent down 
for the third straight year from 35 percent in 1984 
the farmers share of the food dollar dropped to 32 percent in 
1985 and to 31 percent in 1986 
earlier agriculture department estimates had put those readings 
even lower to 31 percent in 1985 30 percent in 1986 and 29 
percent in 1987 
department records show the farm share of each consumer food 
dollar averaged 46 percent in 1913 when recordkeeping began until 
the figure fell to 31 percent in 1986 the record low mark had been 
32 percent in both 1932 and 1933 during the depression the high 
was more than 50 percent in world war ii and for a few years 
thereafter 
the market basket contains average quantities of domestically 
produced food bought in grocery stores excluding nonalcoholic 
beverages and fish and seafood 
one reason for the slippage in the farm value of grocery items 
has been a general weakening of prices for some raw commodities 
but the situation varies greatly from item to item and it depends 
on how much processing is involved 
only a slight amount of raw milk is lost for example as it 
is handled and processed for sale in cartons to consumers the 
report said therefore the farm value of the retail price per 
halfgallon is just a little more than the price that milk 
producers receive per halfgallon 
the report added in contrast nearly 24 pounds of live 
animal are needed to yield one pound of choice beef on the meat 
counter the payment the cattle producer receives for that large 
quantity of live animal is the gross farm value in the price of one 
pound of retail beef 
with the 1987 farm value of groceries at 30 cents of each 
consumer food dollar that means 70 cents went to nonfarmers the 
people who buy transport process and sell food at wholesale and 
retail 
each time the farmers share declines it means a greater 
farmretail share for the others 
ralph parlett a food economist in the agency says the trend to 
a smaller share for farmers also is the result of a growing 
consumer preference for a greater degree of processing in food 
when the farmers share of the food dollar was 45 cents to 49 
cents in the early 1950s there was less processing people bought 
raw food took it home and cooked or preserved it now parlett 
said in a recent telephone interview supermarkets display the 
latest in the processors art 
the products we have today arent the same he said 
microwave products are an example we didnt have those at all a 
few years ago 
also he said the efficiencies of farmers have picked up 
meaning that greater yields are resulting from the same acreages 
more meat from the same amount of feed 
</TEXT>
