campaign strategists for george bush 
say they are trying to win the nations most populous state by 
pursuing not only the reagan democrats but also more moderate 
democrats who might be attracted to a futureoriented 
republican candidate distinct from president reagan 
a number of swing voters are not reagan democrats steve 
merksamer the bush state campaign chairman said in reference to 
those democrats who voted for reagan in the past two elections 
they are more moderate democrats who are not necessarily in 
sinc with reagans conservative ideas 
with a democratic edge in the states voter registration the 
republicans must attract democrats as they have in past elections 
to win the state with the most electoral votes 47 
public opinion polls show the race virtually even making 
california a critical tossup state its diverse economy and broad 
demographic and social makeup makes california an expensive state 
in which to campaign but both candidates are making an allout 
push 
the bush campaign will devote most of its resources in the 
coming weeks to winning swing voters and democrats said senior 
campaign consultant bill lacy who is heading the california 
effort he said the bush forces are confident they have already 
shored up their republican support in the tight contest 
in comments to reporters traveling with the campaign tuesday 
lacy and merksamer refused to disclose projected budget figures for 
the california effort 
the moderate democrats many of whom live in the sacramento 
area do not respond with the same emotional intensity to the 
socalled value issues that are popular with the democrats who 
crossed party lines to give president reagan his two general 
election victories said merksamer 
the campaign believes they are more likely to be swayed by 
speeches like the one bush made here tuesday in which he proposed a 
program to promote volunteer service by young people he said 
the proposal was aimed at showing bush to be a strong leader 
with futureoriented ideas lacy said 
a tv ad attacking democratic presidential nominee michael 
dukakis for the pollution in boston harbor under his governorship 
has played well in california but the bush campaign does not see 
environmental concerns as decisive in the election said merksamer 
he said it is primarily a coastal population that sees the 
environment as a top issue while voters inland are more concerned 
about crime taxes and defense both from a foreign policy 
perspective and an economic one since much of californias economy 
is driven by defense contracting 
besides the boston harbor commercial the campaign has been 
running a crime quiz commercial attacking dukakis and positive 
ads featuring excerpts from bushs lively speech at the republican 
national convention in august and another feelgood ad 
narrated by bushs wife barbara 
