<TEXT>
the house has approved and sent to the senate 
a bill strengthening protection for whistelblowers who expose 
federal waste and mismanagement 
the measure was approved tuesday on a 4180 vote 
sponsors said the bill was needed because the office of special 
counsel established to represent the interests of whistleblowers 
was not doing its job 
the bill is designed to reverse decisions of courts and the 
merit systems protection board a federal judicial agency that 
made it difficult for whistleblowers to win their cases 
the legislation would define clearly the office of special 
counsels role as one of protecting whistleblowers in some cases 
the counsel has proceeded against whistleblowers who came to the 
office for help 
the measure would make the office of special counsel an 
independent agency it currently is part of the merit systems 
protection board a quasijudicial body that hears employees 
appeals 
the bill also would 
alter the burden of proof in reprisal cases against 
whistleblowers the employee would have to show only that the 
agencys knowledge of the whistleblowing was a factor in his or her 
punishment rather than a significant or dominant factor as 
required under current law 
require an agency to demonstrate with clear and convincing 
evidence that whistleblowing was not a material factor in the 
personnel action currently the courts require a preponderance of 
evidence an easier standard for government agencies 
expand the definition of prohibited personnel practices to 
include reprisals against workers who cooperate with inspectors 
general or the special counsel those who testify in government 
proceedings and those who refuse to obey an order that violates 
the law 
allow individuals facing reprisals to appeal their cases 
directly to the merit board 
</TEXT>
