<TEXT>
thousands of troops guarded polling 
places today and voters stood in milelong lines to cast yes or 
no ballots on a proposal to extend president augusto pinochets 
15year rule to 1997 
power outages blamed on terrorist bombings plunged the capital 
and other cities into darkness late tuesday but the country was 
calm as polls opened at 8 am 
by midmorning thousands of voters lined up at santiago voting 
centers waiting patiently under a sunny cloudless sky in warm 
spring weather 
chiles 74 million registered voters are required by law to 
vote some voters said they arrived early for fear of trouble later 
in the day 
pinochet who voted downtown late this morning spoke 
sarcastically of the blackout by using the slogan of the 
opposition its the joy thats coming but the 72yearold 
