<TEXT>
a proposal to ban the mailing of germs and 
dangerous toxins has drown vigorous opposition assistant 
postmaster general frank r heselton said wednesday 
as a result final action on the ban has been postponed until 
the issue can be more fully studied heselton reported to a house 
post office and civil service subcommittee 
and heselton said the postal service has contacted the federal 
centers for disease control and the department of transportation 
for assistance in developing safety standards for hazardous mail 
of 508 comments received after the proposed rule was made 
public only seven favored the ban heselton said opposition for 
various reasons came from doctors laboratories colleges and 
universities medical centers pathologists and biologists and 
state and federal health groups among others he said 
the plan to exclude germs and toxins from the mail was announced 
in june in the wake of reports that the military had increased 
shipments of such items 
the action was taken to ensure the safety and health of 
customers and employees the postal service said in announcing 
the decision the postal service is concerned that some customers 
are planning increased use of the mails for sending disease germs 
or hazardous toxins etiologic agents 
opponents of the restriction contended that there is no record 
of anyone ever being infected by handling mailed germs or toxins 
however 
they said the ban would increase the costs of shipping medical 
materials for testing purposes possibly slow down such testing and 
might lead mailers to improperly package and misidentify such items 
in order to mail them 
the postal service does not want to increase medical costs or 
have a negative impact on medical diagnosis or research heselton 
said but it must also be able to protect both its employees and 
the public 
it may be possible to reduce the risk by reducing the quantity 
permitted for medical purposes per parcel and requiring better 
packaging and more expeditious means of movement in the mail he 
said 
postal workers in kansas city last year expressed concern about 
blood and other medical samples mailed to a laboratory there for 
testing when some packages were found leaking mail handlers were 
supplied with gloves masks and other protective gear at the time 
and the packaging for the samples has since been improved 
postal regulations already prohibit the mailing of a variety of 
items including strikeanywhere matches explosives fuses many 
poisons most flammable liquids and certain chemicals 
many other items such as corrosives compressed gases 
herbicides pesticides and certain other poisons can be mailed 
only in certain types of packages and in specific quantities 
 
