interview the only reason honduras endorsed the plan was to avoid 
being portrayed as an obstacle to peace 
lopez contreras made his statements one day after he spoke to 
the un general assembly and urged the creation of an 
international peace force to evict the usbacked contra rebels 
from honduran territory 
thousands of rebels have settled in the border area since 
congress ended military aid to the contras earlier this year 
the foreign minister proposed that military units from spain 
canada and west germany carry out the evacuation using force if 
necessary 
his proposal appeared to represent a break with reagan 
administration policy but the state department said it was 
reviewing the plan with an open mind 
we will give the honduran proposal serious consideration 
said state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said in 
washington 
even if a peacekeeping force is agreed to such a force only 
would represent a partial solution lopez contreras said 
we cannot stop the soviets from supplying arms to the 
sandinistas he said that is an issue that has to be addressed 
by the united states 
if there is not a minimum of understanding between them it is 
going to be absolutely impossible to reach any kind of settlement 
in central america lopez contreras declared 
he said international organizations such as the united nations 
cannot expect honduras by itself to resolve a problem created in 
part by superpower policies 
the soviet position reiterated in talks in washington last 
month is that the kremlin would cease arms deliveries to nicaragua 
if the united states suspends lethal aid to its allies in central 
america the reagan administration has rejected that proposal 
foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze of the soviet union said 
after his talks in washington on sept 23 that the gap between the 
two countries positions had not narrowed 
assistant secretary of state elliott abrams is expected to hold 
additional discussions with soviet officials on central america 
later this month 
