church bells rang in this modernistic 
capital wednesday as brazil enacted its eighth constitution 
consolidating the switchover from military rule to civilian 
government that began in 1985 
the 559 legislators who for 19 months battled over the 
245article document cheered and shouted brazil is changing 
as the president of the constituent assembly ulysses guimaraes 
declared law the new document 
i declare enacted the constitution of liberty of dignity of 
democracy and social justice guimaraes 72 said in a voice that 
struggled above thunderous applause may god help us enforce it 
brazils new democratic charter leaves behind the old 
authoritarian document that was handed down by military generals in 
1969 
the enactment was the last step in brazils return to fully 
democratic rule begun in march 1985 when jose sarney became 
brazils first civilian president since a 1964 rightwing military 
coup 
we have created a new brazil a new social and economic 
order dante de oliveira of the governing democratic movement 
party said after the ceremony we have taught the world an 
important lesson peacefully overturning an authoritarian regime 
the new document a mixture of leftleaning conservative and 
nationalistic articles that touch almost all aspects of life from 
land reform to interest rates granted none of the arbitrary powers 
used by the repressive military government during 21 years to rule 
the country 
the new charter bans censorship removes the presidents power 
to simply decree law and outlaws torture which in the past was 
used against the military governments political opponents 
but many of the articles were confusing several such as a 
reduced work week more maternity leave and extra pay for overtime 
immediately became law 154 would need complimentary legislation to 
become effective 
one such confusing article limited real interest rates to 12 
percent though no one knows what real interest rates in 
inflationridden brazil are inflation in brazil is averaging more 
than 350 percent over the last 12 months 
one of the most controversial articles fought over by 
legislators who shouted each other down in daylong debates and 
often resorted to physical violence set presidential elections in 
november 1989 brazilians havent voted for president since 1960 
representatives from 21 latin american and portuguesespeaking 
nations watched legislators enact brazils eighth constitution 
since the country gained independence from portugal in 1822 
</TEXT>
