<TEXT>
despite watergateinspired curbs on election 
spending millions of dollars are pouring into republican and 
democratic campaign treasuries from fat cat contributors this fall 
and its all legal 
documents made available to reporters recently show that both 
political parties are avidly courting the kind of bigmoney 
donations that were tarnished by revelations of watergateera 
abuses and then supposedly curtailed by election law reforms of the 
1970s 
the biggest republican contributor is nicholas salgo former 
us ambassador to hungary who was listed as giving more than 
500000 to his party the democrats say a couple of unidentified 
unions are giving 200000 each 
both parties are going after individuals willing to give 
100000 or more the gop claims it has 115 such givers so far in 
the 1988 campaign the democratic national committee counts 100 fat 
cats with a goal of doubling the number 
these funds are known as soft money because federal law 
prohibits unions and corporations from making direct contributions 
to federal election campaigns and limits individuals to giving 
1000 in presidential primaries only 
in the general election the presidential nominees are forbidden 
to accept any private donations because each receives 461 million 
from a treasury fund supported by the voluntary 1 checkoff on 
individual income tax returns plus 83 million from his party 
so millions of dollars in soft money are funneled through the 
parties to finance political activities at the state and local 
level which are not subject to federal regulation even at that 
level the parties have no trouble finding ways to use soft money 
for activities such as voter registration and tv commercials that 
clearly benefit their presidential candidates 
what is happening in 1988 is its becoming clearer and 
clearer that soft money is making a joke of the campaign finance 
laws said ellen miller director of the center for responsive 
politics a research organization that advocates tightening 
campaign finance laws 
the list of soft money receipts released by the democrats which 
covers only june and july included 48 million of about 15 
million the party has raised in soft money so far 
no public accounting of soft money is required and the 
democrats say they will make no further fundraising disclosures 
until after the nov 8 elections 
robert farmer fundraising chief for democratic nominee michael 
dukakis and head of the victory fund says the party has a 50 
million goal this year with about 20 million coming from 
bigspending individuals 
the gop files showed 10 million in soft money raised through 
midseptember but did not include details of an additional 16 
million raised by a victory 88 operation and slated for 
separate accounts in each state 
party officials say the victory 88 goal is to raise 25 million 
in the states while another soft money program team 100 will 
bring in about 15 million 
vice president george bush the republican nominee frequently 
attends glittery fundraising events in banquet halls or private 
homes to help bolster the gops victory 88 effort farmer 
mines the telephone network of wealthy democratic donors and 
concentrates on bigticket galas featuring dukakis 
while raising millions of dollars in soft money the two major 
parties are stretching the rules to the limit but they nonetheless 
are acting legally under guidelines which the federal election 
commission is under court order to tighten up 
despite the federal ban on direct contributions to the 
candidates party officials make support for bush or dukakis a big 
part of their pitch to potential donors 
we make it quite clear that they are not contributing to 
michael dukakis said don sweitzer finance director for the 
democratic national committee michael dukakis is on the 
democratic ticket and therefore he benefits indirectly from these 
funds theyre inspired by the head of the ticket to support the 
entire ticket 
florida developer joe zappala cochairman of republicans team 
100 group of 100000 donors said that when you talk about 
george bush people are fairly receptive 
zappalas tactic goes like this you apprise people of the 
cost to run an election its expensive we tell them we are 
running behind in fund raising we dont want to lose an election 
because we are running out of money 
the democrats traditionally the fundraising underdogs say 
they have collected 38 million toward their 50 million goal this 
year of that sum sweitzer said about 15 million is in soft 
money 
contrary to the ominous warnings in zappalas pitch the gop 
national committee boasts 67 million in overall receipts so far 
this year 
of that total 13 million is soft money being raised in state 
accounts toward a goal of 25 million plus nearly 10 million that 
has come from fat cat donors pricey galas and the partys 
eagle program of 10000peryear givers 
both parties say its not easy persuading individuals to give 
100000 or more but there seem to be plenty of willing donors 
people are surprised they can give that much zappala said 
theres been a lot of concerns about the federal legal limits we 
explain to them it is legal 
</TEXT>
