in launching a 517 billion bid for 
pillsbury co britains grand metropolitan plc is proposing to 
strip pillsbury of a division that has helped make the company 
vulnerable to a takeover 
grand metropolitan said in a filing with the securities and 
exchange commission that if its 60ashare bid begun tuesday 
succeeds it would sell pillsburys steak amp ale and bennigans 
restaurant operations 
the underperforming fullservice restaurant division was 
restructured in january resulting in a 91 million charge that has 
dragged down earnings the restructuring also precipitated 
management changes including the hiring of former general foods 
corp chairman philip l smith as its own new chairman in july 
grand metropolitan indicated it would sell steak amp ale and 
bennigans because of state laws prohibiting a company from owning 
both alcoholic beverage makers and retailers 
pillsbury is using that issue to challenge the takeover bid 
although by tuesday it had not actually or approved of the offer 
in a statement issued late tuesday smith said pillsbury had 
sued to block the acquisition in 13 states contending a buyout by 
grand met would violate liquor laws prohibiting producers from 
owning liquor retailers 
courts in texas oklahoma new mexico michigan kansas 
pennsylvania and missouri have issued temporary restraining orders 
enjoining grand met from acquiring any pillsbury stock and a 
delaware court has rejected grand mets effort to stop those 
actions pillsbury said 
grand met a 10 billion a year diversified company is one of 
the worlds biggest wine and spirit makers with brands that 
include smirnoff vodka jampb scotch gilbeys gin watney and ushers 
ale and almaden wines 
