<TEXT>
the navy on wednesday awarded the general 
dynamics corp a 6174 million contract for a new trident missile 
submarine slashing more than 266 million off the price it paid 
last year 
navy officials said the award demonstrated they had been right 
in pressing a virginia shipyard to compete against general dynamics 
more than a year ago even if general dynamics ultimately succeeded 
in protecting its monopoly on the huge subs 
it shows the benefits of competition said lt ken ross a 
navy spokesman that previous competition is still bearing 
fruit 
the contract awarded wednesday represents the first of two 
options in a contract initially awarded by the navy in january 
after competitive bidding between general dynamics and the newport 
news shipbuilding amp drydock co 
the award to general dynamics electric boat division in groton 
conn covers the one trident submarine authorized by congress in 
the fiscal 1989 budget and will be the 16th in the line 
the fixedprice contract specifies the trident should be 
delivered by october 1994 the navy has said it wants to order at 
least 20 tridents and possibly more 
with the exception of nuclearpowered aircraft carriers the 
trident program was the last major navy shipbuilding program to be 
opened to competition newport news shipbuilding a division of 
tenneco inc enjoys a monopoly on the construction of aircraft 
carriers in part because no other shipyard has the massive 
facilities required to build that type of ship 
in november 1987 newport news accepted a navy request that it 
compete against general dynamics in the trident program it 
submitted a bid for the fiscal 1988 sub as well as option bids on 
the two additional boats expected to be purchased in fiscal 1989 
and fiscal 1990 
general dynamics did the same and last jan 5 the navy 
announced general dynamics had succeeded in preserving its monopoly 
by underbidding newport news the navy awarded the firm a 644 
million contract for the fiscal 1988 submarine without revealing 
what either company had bid for the two option years 
ross said wednesday the navy believes it will save roughly 100 
million over the life of the contract if the second option is also 
exercised 
the spokesman said the latest award reverses what has been a 
spiraling price for the huge vessels the fiscal 1986 submarine 
cost the navy about 587 million the price climbed to 615 million 
in fiscal 1987 then rose again in january to 644 million 
this contract is cutting more than 26 million off that fiscal 
1988 buy ross said 
the 560foot trident submarines also known as the ohio class 
are considered the most survivable leg of americas nuclear 
arsenal each of the vessels can carry 24 longrange multiwarhead 
nuclear missiles and remain submerged for months at a time 
each of the subs when completely outfitted with nuclear 
reactors and governmentfurnished equipment cost more than 14 
billion eight of the submarines are already commissioned on active 
duty and a ninth the uss tennessee will soon join them 
